## Part 2: The Provider Pattern (1.5 hours)

### 2.1 Understanding Providers

A **provider** is an abstraction for a backend service:

```go
// In pkg/provider/database.go

// Interface: what we depend on (contract)
type DatabaseProvider interface {
    Connect(ctx context.Context) (*sql.DB, error)
    DB() *sql.DB
    Close() error
    Name() string
}

// Concrete implementation: how we do it
type PostgreSQLProvider struct {
    config *Config
    db     *sql.DB
}

func (p *PostgreSQLProvider) Connect(ctx context.Context) (*sql.DB, error) {
    db, err := sql.Open("postgres", p.config.DSN)
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }
    p.db = db
    return db, nil
}

func (p *PostgreSQLProvider) DB() *sql.DB {
    return p.db
}

func (p *PostgreSQLProvider) Close() error {
    return p.db.Close()
}
```

### 2.2 Why Providers Matter

```go
// Without providers (tightly coupled):
func GetUser(id string) {
    db := sql.Open("postgres", "...")  // Hardcoded!
    // Query...
}
// Problem: Can't test, can't switch databases

// With providers (loosely coupled):
type UserRepository struct {
    db DatabaseProvider  // Depends on interface, not implementation
}

func (r *UserRepository) GetUser(id string) {
    r.db.DB().QueryRow(...)
}

// In tests: Use mock provider
// In production: Use PostgreSQL provider
```

### 2.3 Ellume Core Provider Usage

```go
// In inithandler/providers.go
func InitProviders(cfg *config.Config) (DatabaseProvider, AuthProvider) {
    // Database
    dbProvider := dbProvider.NewPostgreSQLProvider(&dbProvider.Config{
        Driver: cfg.Database.Driver,
        DSN:    cfg.Database.DSN,
    })

    // Auth
    var authProvider authProvider.AuthProvider
    switch cfg.Auth.Provider {
    case "firebase":
        authProvider = authProvider.NewFirebaseProvider(...)
    case "cognito":
        authProvider = authProvider.NewCognitoProvider(...)
    default:
        authProvider = authProvider.NewMockProvider()
    }

    return dbProvider, authProvider
}
```

